%N A389517 Number of ways to write 2*n as an unordered sum of four primes with square indices.
%C A389517 Recall that a prime with square index has the form prime(k^2).
%C A389517 Conjecture: a(n) > 0 for any integer n > 3286, i.e., any even number greater than 6572 is a sum of four terms from A011757.
%C A389517 This conjecture is motivated by the Goldbach conjecture and Lagrange's four-square theorem. We have verified it for n <= 250000.
%C A389517 It seems that 5368 is the largest value of n with a(n) = 1.
%C A389517 See also A389525 for a similar conjecture.
%C A389517 From _Chai Wah Wu_, Oct 09 2025: (Start)
%C A389517 a(n) > 0 for 3287 <= n <= 7.7*10^6.
%C A389517   k     conjectured largest value of n for which a(n) = k
%C A389517 ----------------
%C A389517   2      6977
%C A389517   3     11935
%C A389517   4     13654
%C A389517   5     12310
%C A389517   6     20242
%C A389517   7     21043
%C A389517   8     18250
%C A389517   9     18820
%C A389517  10     21958
%C A389517 (End)
%C A389517 Conjecture: for all k, there exists n_k such that a(m)>k for all m >= n_k. - _Chai Wah Wu_, Oct 15 2025
%H A389517 Zhi-Wei Sun, <a href="/A389517/b389517.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000</a>
%H A389517 Zhi-Wei Sun, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jnt.2016.11.008">Refining Lagrange's four-square theorem</a>, J. Number Theory 175(2017), 167-190. Also available from <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/1604.06723">arXiv:1604.06723 [math.NT]</a>, 2016-2017.
%e A389517 a(25) = 1 with prime(1^2) + prime(1^2) + prime(3^2) + prime(3^2) = 2 + 2 + 23 + 23 = 2*25.
%e A389517 a(5115) = 1 with prime(4^2) + prime(5^2) + prime(21^2) + prime(30^2) = 53 + 97 + 3083 + 6997 = 2*5115.
%e A389517 a(5368) = 1 with prime(3^2) + prime(5^2) + prime(17^2) + prime(33^2) = 23 + 97 + 1879 + 8737 = 2*5368.
